cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.CL, cs.CYBER, cs.CR 

This paper focuses on studying intercommunity interactions and conflicts on web platforms, which involves analyzing user behavior and language. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Additionally, the paper also touches upon topics related to online communities and their dynamics, which falls under cs.SOC (Social and Behavioral Sciences). The use of machine learning techniques for predicting conflicts and user participation suggests a possible fit with cs.CL (Computation and Language) and cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy). Finally, the paper also discusses the adverse effects of conflicts, which could be relevant to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
